metadata.name: p5js tutorials - Record Array #14
metadata.description:
A 'simple' p5 tutorial for you creative coders

Recording the x,y positions when you draw
in a buffer / Array

To keep track where things are drawn on the screen
And use these new positions, as a platform-start
to draw other shapes.

It's an easy / fun trick to keep track of things you've drawn on the screen

 I use this trick as well in 3D; 
for like drawing trees, then the branches and leaves


See the sketch here.
https://editor.p5js.org/elout/sketches/qNlUda02j

Feel free, to change and adjust it -->>> all <<<--- around.
And feel free, to learn from the source - example

- s key saves the 1500x1500 image; when the sketch is open/selected

fx* 
The source of this fxhash-sketch is just a  bit different, though.
Since I adjusted it for publishing it on fxhash
You can use and change this source on fxhash as well!


xxx amsterdam chillout ^__^

metadata.name: Tangentum #114
metadata.description:
We live in a multiverse: an infinite-dimensional space of variants. Everything exists here. Everything is possible. Each subset of a multiverse has its own unique laws of physics, a set of rules, and its own distinct features.

Tangentum creates a projection of a random multiverse subset to a 2-dimensional plane. Each variation is a unique representation of the force field, that exists somewhere at some point in time.

This work starts a series of my visual exploration of functions, continuity, and boundedness, and I would love to share it with you.


Please use fullscreen or download artwork in high resolution for a better viewing experience.

Tested with Chrome 107, Safari, and Firefox. Chrome is recommended, other browsers are slower on this artwork.

Saving with high and ultra-high resolution may take a while, please be patient.


Made with love and p5js


Controls in fullscreen:
[1] - save PNG 2700 x 1800
[2] - save PNG 5400 x 3800
[3] - save PNG 10800 x 7600
[4] - save PNG 16200 x 11400

metadata.name: Ars Mystica #8
metadata.description:
As the artist sat at her computer, she couldn't help but feel a sense of excitement and anticipation. She had spent months refining her generative art piece, a jungle of shapes that seemed to pulse and swirl with life. Using the rough.js library, she had crafted each and every one of the shapes with precise control, carefully balancing order and chaos to create a mesmerizing and dynamic piece of art.

Finally, she was ready to unveil her creation to the world. She hit the "publish" button, and the art piece went live on fxhash. Within minutes, the responses started pouring in. People from all over the world were marveling at the jungle of shapes, each one a unique and intricate creation.

As the artist sat back and watched the reactions roll in, she couldn't help but feel a sense of pride and accomplishment. She had poured her heart and soul into this piece, and it seemed to be resonating with people in a way she could have never imagined. And as she gazed at the jungle of shapes on her screen, she knew that this was only the beginning. There were so many more art pieces waiting to be created, and she couldn't wait to see where her imagination would take her next.

In live mode Press "s" to save image (2200 x 3030).

+---+
Ars Mystica by __Reiji_c
+---+
Made with vanilla javascript + (roughjs MIT License (c) Preet Shihn)

metadata.name: Paper City Dreams #28
metadata.description:
A city made of paper,
crafted with care,
using RoughJS and Hashure Gap
to build buildings with flair.

Rectangles stacked on top of each other,
cast shadows on the ground,
a cross-hash adding depth
to the structures all around.

A city of lines and shapes,
a city of texture and hue,
a generative art masterpiece
bringing the paper city to life, anew.

In live mode press "s" to save image (2200 x 3030).

This may take some time to render, please wait.

metadata.name: Bougainvillea #179
Bougainvillea #154
Bougainvillea #131
Bougainvillea #7
Brosser #191
metadata.description:
Exploring generative brush strokes to simulate real life paintings. 

- A selection of 19 different palettes
- 4 different drawing styles
- Randomized "color swap" between the primary and secondary colors in each palette

Several other factors determine the output of a piece, including angles, depth, brush length, and brush weight, among others.

metadata.name: Handachak #47
metadata.description:
I have always been looking for solutions that can connect different visual elements in such a way as to create an integrated system and structure and each part of the work plays its own role in this system.
Another point is that always attributing physical characteristics to abstract forms creates aesthetic qualities. From a general point of view, one of these features is perspective, and in this project we see a type of perspective in an abstract and geometric structure.
"Handachak" means "Geometry" in ancient Persian.
